00:00:10.110 --> 00:00:11.660
PETER: Welcome to
Authors at Google

00:00:11.660 --> 00:00:13.400
and welcome to Alex Bellos.

00:00:13.400 --> 00:00:15.660
I don't know if any of
you saw his earlier talk

00:00:15.660 --> 00:00:18.990
a couple of years ago around
his first book, "Adventures

00:00:18.990 --> 00:00:21.790
in Numberland,"
which was a huge hit.

00:00:21.790 --> 00:00:24.200
And on a personal business,
it was a huge hit for me

00:00:24.200 --> 00:00:27.620
because my 10-year-old
son at the time

00:00:27.620 --> 00:00:29.490
I couldn't get him to
read any books at all.

00:00:29.490 --> 00:00:31.240
And in desperation,
we were on holiday,

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:33.365
and I kind of handed him
"Adventures in Numberland"

00:00:33.365 --> 00:00:34.940
and said have a look at this.

00:00:34.940 --> 00:00:36.880
And he quickly became
extremely hooked on

00:00:36.880 --> 00:00:41.370
and spent the entire holiday
going yam, tan, tethera which

00:00:41.370 --> 00:00:44.470
I'm sure you'll know is the
ancient English way of counting

00:00:44.470 --> 00:00:45.210
sheep.

00:00:45.210 --> 00:00:47.557
And when you get to
15, it's bumfit I

00:00:47.557 --> 00:00:48.640
think I'm right in saying.

00:00:48.640 --> 00:00:52.120
And he spent the entire
holiday talking about bumfit.

00:00:52.120 --> 00:00:55.290
So it sort of both hooked
him in an interest in maths

00:00:55.290 --> 00:00:57.040
and gave him a license
to use bad language

00:00:57.040 --> 00:00:58.600
so it was kind of perfect.

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:02.490
So the new book is "Alex
Through the Looking-glass."

00:01:02.490 --> 00:01:04.560
Alex is going to
talk for half an hour

00:01:04.560 --> 00:01:06.089
or so and then take
some questions?

00:01:06.089 --> 00:01:08.380
ALEX BELLOS: A little bit
more than that but, because I

00:01:08.380 --> 00:01:09.860
want to be very informal,
so if there's anything

00:01:09.860 --> 00:01:11.890
you don't understand or you
want more, just shout out,

00:01:11.890 --> 00:01:12.740
put your hand up.

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:14.800
So let's kind of have
the kind of Q and A

00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:18.470
as we go I think because
we're a little bit delayed.

00:01:18.470 --> 00:01:19.908
I'm going to have to--

00:01:19.908 --> 00:01:21.616
PETER: And I'll hand
if over [INAUDIBLE].

00:01:21.616 --> 00:01:22.060
Keep going.

00:01:22.060 --> 00:01:22.559
Cheers.

00:01:25.864 --> 00:01:27.780
ALEX BELLOS: Usually,
I'm used to giving talks

00:01:27.780 --> 00:01:32.240
to book festivals where the
kind of mathematical numeracy

00:01:32.240 --> 00:01:34.700
is going to be a lot lower
than you guys are here

00:01:34.700 --> 00:01:36.560
so I might whip through
it but you might

00:01:36.560 --> 00:01:40.720
have slightly more
high-brow questions.

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:41.990
So thank you very much, Peter.

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:43.220
I'm Alex Bellos.

00:01:43.220 --> 00:01:46.011
This is me.

00:01:46.011 --> 00:01:46.510
Oh, my god.

00:01:46.510 --> 00:01:47.551
I just pressed something.

00:01:50.700 --> 00:01:54.970
That's me with a weird
stain on my red jumper.

00:01:54.970 --> 00:01:56.570
I don't know why
I was given that.

00:01:56.570 --> 00:01:59.300
And this is my new book, "Alex
Through the Looking-glass,"

00:01:59.300 --> 00:02:02.330
which sounds very much like it's
a sequel to "Alex's Adventures

00:02:02.330 --> 00:02:05.530
in Numberland" but
it isn't really.

00:02:05.530 --> 00:02:07.779
Both can be read separately.

00:02:07.779 --> 00:02:10.070
You don't need to have read
the first one to read this.

00:02:10.070 --> 00:02:12.340
If there is a
difference, the first one

00:02:12.340 --> 00:02:16.750
was just an exploration about
mathematical abstraction

00:02:16.750 --> 00:02:18.240
and what we get when we use it.

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:20.820
This is a little bit
more kind of applied.

00:02:20.820 --> 00:02:24.112
It's about using
abstraction to learn

00:02:24.112 --> 00:02:26.570
about the world, mathematics
being the language that we use

00:02:26.570 --> 00:02:28.780
to talk about the
world, and also

00:02:28.780 --> 00:02:30.920
how life reflects numbers
and numbers reflect life.

00:02:30.920 --> 00:02:34.180
I also wanted to get into
kind of psychology of numbers

00:02:34.180 --> 00:02:36.035
and interesting
psychological responses

00:02:36.035 --> 00:02:40.680
that we have to numbers which
are quite surprising I think

00:02:40.680 --> 00:02:43.810
and definitely under-researched.

00:02:43.810 --> 00:02:47.931
Now, how do you write a
book on maths and numbers

00:02:47.931 --> 00:02:48.930
and make it interesting.

00:02:48.930 --> 00:02:54.590
It's quite difficult because
the nature of the subject is dry

00:02:54.590 --> 00:02:58.490
and sometimes it's
conceptually challenging.

00:02:58.490 --> 00:03:02.220
So I've got a degree
in maths and philosophy

00:03:02.220 --> 00:03:03.850
and then I became a journalist.

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:06.130
So my approach is
always to tell stories.

00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:07.790
And I think that
by telling stories,

00:03:07.790 --> 00:03:10.010
if you can interest
someone in the story,

00:03:10.010 --> 00:03:13.214
then you don't need
to say, oh, by the way

00:03:13.214 --> 00:03:14.630
I'm going to teach
you some maths.

00:03:14.630 --> 00:03:17.630
You just learn the
maths on the way.

00:03:17.630 --> 00:03:21.080
And where do you
look for stories?

00:03:21.080 --> 00:03:24.580
Well, the kind of classic
place to look for a story

00:03:24.580 --> 00:03:26.050
is in oneself.

00:03:26.050 --> 00:03:30.760
And so, actually, my story as
a popularizer of mathematics

00:03:30.760 --> 00:03:33.570
is really where
this book begins.

00:03:33.570 --> 00:03:36.400
And I have to say I don't
think it happened at my talk

00:03:36.400 --> 00:03:39.870
at Google last time, but pretty
much every talk that I did

00:03:39.870 --> 00:03:42.340
when the first book came out,
I would give what I thought

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:45.459
was a fantastically fascinating
talk about maths and numbers.

00:03:45.459 --> 00:03:47.500
And someone would put
their hand at the end of it

00:03:47.500 --> 00:03:49.060
and they would say, yes, sir.

00:03:49.060 --> 00:03:52.856
And they would just say, so
what's your favorite number?

00:03:52.856 --> 00:03:54.230
And I can just
remember thinking,

00:03:54.230 --> 00:03:56.207
oh, have you learned nothing?

00:03:56.207 --> 00:03:57.290
Who has a favorite number?

00:03:57.290 --> 00:03:57.850
I'm grown-up.

00:03:57.850 --> 00:03:59.060
You're a grown-up.

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:01.226
And I would just think they
were kind of teasing me.

00:04:01.226 --> 00:04:03.580
It was way of belittling
the subject on myself.

00:04:03.580 --> 00:04:06.490
Until I kept on being
asked this question.

00:04:06.490 --> 00:04:09.140
I would give talks
at universities,

00:04:09.140 --> 00:04:11.530
secondary schools,
books festivals.

00:04:11.530 --> 00:04:13.331
People were always asking it.

00:04:13.331 --> 00:04:14.955
So once I just said,
oh, I didn't know.

00:04:14.955 --> 00:04:16.269
What's your favorite number?

00:04:16.269 --> 00:04:22.000
But rather than saying,
ah, they went, oh, 12,

00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:23.510
gave me a considered response.

00:04:23.510 --> 00:04:24.924
And I just was like, what?

00:04:24.924 --> 00:04:26.840
And then the person next
to them said, oh, no,

00:04:26.840 --> 00:04:29.045
my favorite number is 13.

00:04:29.045 --> 00:04:31.500
I said, well, who here's
got favorite numbers?

00:04:31.500 --> 00:04:34.390
And at least half the
audience of grown-ups

00:04:34.390 --> 00:04:35.830
put their hands up.

00:04:35.830 --> 00:04:37.500
And this happened
a few more times.

00:04:37.500 --> 00:04:39.280
So I thought, well,
this is interesting.

00:04:39.280 --> 00:04:42.350
From being something that I
thought was completely idiotic,

00:04:42.350 --> 00:04:45.920
I thought, well, if
grown-up people who

00:04:45.920 --> 00:04:50.470
are literate and numerate
have serious [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:50.470 --> 00:04:52.820
emotional reactions
numbers, this is interesting

00:04:52.820 --> 00:04:54.580
and why don't I try
and research it?

00:04:54.580 --> 00:05:02.650
And so what I did is I thought
I would undergo a survey

00:05:02.650 --> 00:05:04.870
to try and find the
world's favorite number.

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:06.620
But essentially it was
to try and quantify

00:05:06.620 --> 00:05:08.170
emotional responses to numbers.

00:05:08.170 --> 00:05:12.970
So I set up this website
here, favouritenumber.net.

00:05:12.970 --> 00:05:15.440
I realized it was going to
have to be international,

00:05:15.440 --> 00:05:18.870
so I also bought this
one, favoritenumber.net,

00:05:18.870 --> 00:05:20.830
just so no one was excluded.

00:05:20.830 --> 00:05:23.385
And within a few
weeks-- at that time,

00:05:23.385 --> 00:05:25.760
four years ago, I maybe had
only a few thousand followers

00:05:25.760 --> 00:05:26.569
on Twitter.

00:05:26.569 --> 00:05:27.610
I just put it on Twitter.

00:05:27.610 --> 00:05:29.110
What's your favorite number?

00:05:29.110 --> 00:05:30.320
Join my survey.

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:34.640
Within a few weeks,
more than 30,000 people

00:05:34.640 --> 00:05:36.794
from around the
world had replied.

00:05:36.794 --> 00:05:38.710
And so this was already
vindicating this idea.

00:05:38.710 --> 00:05:40.650
This is something
that serious people

00:05:40.650 --> 00:05:42.090
feel passionately about it.

00:05:42.090 --> 00:05:44.120
Now, what were the results?

00:05:44.120 --> 00:05:48.160
The results were this.

00:05:48.160 --> 00:05:51.690
7, 3, 8, 4, 5, 13, 9, 6, 2, 11.

00:05:51.690 --> 00:05:55.660
Which "Metro" said was
the most confusing top 10

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:57.962
list ever written.

00:05:57.962 --> 00:05:58.950
Which it is.

00:05:58.950 --> 00:06:00.700
Now, if you go back
to favoritenumber.net,

00:06:00.700 --> 00:06:02.033
I have all the results up there.

00:06:02.033 --> 00:06:03.550
There's a big Excel file of all.

00:06:03.550 --> 00:06:05.687
There's more than 1,000
individual numbers

00:06:05.687 --> 00:06:06.770
and all their frequencies.

00:06:06.770 --> 00:06:09.030
And you can get
them there if you

00:06:09.030 --> 00:06:11.730
are interested to do
an analysis on them,

00:06:11.730 --> 00:06:13.267
if you have a statistical mind.

00:06:13.267 --> 00:06:14.850
But what was interesting
was that when

00:06:14.850 --> 00:06:22.030
I launched the results, it
was an actual news story.

00:06:22.030 --> 00:06:25.550
Again, showing that people
are interested in this stuff.

00:06:25.550 --> 00:06:27.760
It was a news story
in the "Times."

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:31.840
It was a news story in the
"Daily Mail" of all places.

00:06:31.840 --> 00:06:33.820
But it also started
going around the world.

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:36.860
This is "Glamour"
magazine in Paris.

00:06:36.860 --> 00:06:39.760
And I don't think I
found one country that

00:06:39.760 --> 00:06:41.250
didn't report it in some way.

00:06:41.250 --> 00:06:42.750
Just going to mention
a few of them.

00:06:42.750 --> 00:06:44.110
Hungary.

00:06:44.110 --> 00:06:47.870
Hungary has a huge brilliant
mathematical tradition.

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:51.560
And per capita, I think
that more Hungarians entered

00:06:51.560 --> 00:06:53.740
the survey than
any other nation,

00:06:53.740 --> 00:06:55.940
so they were really
fascinated by it.

00:06:55.940 --> 00:06:58.100
Obviously, it was
[INAUDIBLE] Greek,

00:06:58.100 --> 00:07:02.520
Greece being the beginnings
of Western thought.

00:07:02.520 --> 00:07:04.150
By the time, it got
to India, I was now

00:07:04.150 --> 00:07:05.233
a Brazilian mathematician.

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:10.150
But India-- there
are certain countries

00:07:10.150 --> 00:07:12.440
where mathematics and the
idea of doing arithmetic

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:14.620
is really an important
part of national identity.

00:07:14.620 --> 00:07:18.940
And so it was all over the
regional press in India.

00:07:18.940 --> 00:07:21.440
Vietnam, and obviously
I can't read Vietnamese.

00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:23.000
And it just became
quite interesting

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:25.690
what happens in the different
photo archives countries

00:07:25.690 --> 00:07:27.080
when you put in seven.

00:07:27.080 --> 00:07:29.200
This is what you get
when you're in Vietnam.

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:31.610
And when you're in China,
this is what you get.

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:36.330
So it was a new story.

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:40.250
But what is the
moment that you really

00:07:40.250 --> 00:07:42.820
know that it has touched
the public consciousness,

00:07:42.820 --> 00:07:45.070
it's become a real news story?

00:07:45.070 --> 00:07:52.420
It's when you're a
question-- volume, please?

00:07:52.420 --> 00:07:56.840
Three days afterwards, it was
on "Have I Got News for You."

